13. Horizontal Decoupling

[00:00:00]

what's up crafters? Khalil here and in this video we're going to talk about the next essential which is horizontal decoupling.

Now we just learned about vertical slicing, right? We saw that features are made from operations, and those operations, they cut into the system. Hopefully that was clear.

So if we're making an API call, you can expect that what's going to happen is that API call will talk to, let's say, an Express web server that will talk to a controller.

That might pass off control to a service and then maybe a repository to get some data and then maybe another object, a domain layer object which would do some work, maybe some validation logic before finally using the repository. I know we haven't talked about repositories just yet, but we will talk about these in the

pattern first phase.

Ultimately we do all of this [00:01:00] work in an operation, and then we return the request, and then we continue along with the next operation. So that is what is happening in an operation, which is a type of vertical slice, but it's important to actually break down what an operation is made of.

Another major maintainability problem that occurs is when we're doing all of this different type of work. We have work that has to do with accepting requests, work that has to do with dealing with edge cases, work that has to do with validating and being more concerned with things that have to do with the way the business works.

All of these different categories of work that has to get done in an operation, we call these different categories "Concerns". There's a design principle called separation of concerns, and the idea here is that we want to group similar categories of work together, and separate out and make sure that we don't have any lines of [00:02:00] code or "Responsibilities", from a responsibility first point of view,

we want to make sure that we don't have any of these lines of code or responsibilities that live in the wrong place.

And the reason why we do this is twofold.

For Example, if the database connection wasn't working, it would be very good for us to have the code that deals with the database live in a particular place.

This will help us reduce duplication, Because when we have a lot of duplication We don't know where things belong and we end up in this situation where everyone is just writing code in random places And that's what turns it into mush.

So what we want here is some order some structure and A clear place for abstractions to go.

So the way I break up this idea of horizontal decoupling is to do two things.

the first thing is to be aware of what the well known layers of abstraction are.

So you can see in this image we have an infrastructure layer, an adapter layer, [00:03:00] application, domain, and those are the common, well known layers of abstraction. This comes from an architectural style called layered architectures. But this is just so foundational to the way that Architecture works in the wild, and you might be familiar with a less mature version of this which is just MVC, but this particular way of making sense of where responsibilities live, which abstractions they live within, and where those abstractions belong and how those abstractions talk to each other this is something that is just well known, well practiced by the phronimos developers, by the expert developers, and they've been doing this for quite some time and they've had a lot of success with it.

This means that there are certain things that are allowed to happen and certain things that are not allowed to happen. What do I mean by that? What I mean is that the abstractions you create, we are actually able to stereotype those abstractions.

[00:04:00] For example, if you are building a React component, does what? It takes in user data, and it passes that off to something else. That is ultimately all of a React component should do. It should be doing presenting and it should be doing accepting input and passing it off.

Another word for that is interfacing, but ultimately we categorize this concept of interfacing to the infrastructure layer.

So a react component should not know about, let's say, a database. It should not have access directly to a database at all.

We'll talk about all of these in more depth and more detail, what each of these layers of abstraction are, the different types of patterns that you're going to encounter on both the front end and the back end. The way that they play together, how they work and what they do and how we categorize them all a little bit later on. But the important thing to note here right now is that there is a set established directionality to the way that the patterns, the abstractions we're creating should interact with each other.[00:05:00]

This all comes from the Layered Architecture which has many different ways of implementing it.

I guarantee you've heard about the clean architecture, the onion, or the ports and adapters, the hexagonal architecture.

It is all related, it all pieces together, so the first part of horizontal decoupling is this aspect of just making sure that we're putting our abstractions in the right place and using the correct abstractions instead of using no abstractions and just writing code.

Then the second part of horizontal decoupling is actually about well decoupling. So as a request is going to come in from express, let's say on the back end. If we're dealing with Express, or the controller that we use with Express.

A problem that we're going to learn about in the best practice first phase of craftship, is sometimes we want to test things without actually bringing everything along for the ride.

So if I just wanted to test a feature purely, the application and the domain layer, this is the layer that's going to contain all of my edge cases, and all of the business logic, and all of the business [00:06:00] rules, and all the validation rules, so on and so forth, policies, this and that.

It's a very rich area of code with a lot to test, because it. Relates directly to the way the business works.

But in order to get access to it, I need to start up the entirety of the app and just test it all as an end to end test that's going to make my tests very slow, and it's not something that I'm going to want to do, especially when we begin to talk about how we can write our tests and get them to run in a deployment pipeline later on.

Ultimately what we need is more testing options and the skill that is going to give you more testing options is the skill of dependency inversion using contracts to invert dependencies and to isolate specifically the layers that you want to test out so This is getting a little bit more into one of the other essentials, which is called subject or system verification.

But for now, Do we know where responsibilities belong? The lines of [00:07:00] code that we write into the correct abstractions and have them collaborate with the correct ones? And are we able to decouple those abstractions from each other strategically so that we can isolate and place boundaries around particular aspects of our code base, the system that we want to verify.

And if we have this clear picture of where abstractions belong, how they interact, We're going to have more testing options, we're going to have way more maintainable, way more flexible code, and it's going to give you the confidence to feel like you can forego everything you've learned and write mush sometimes and then know what you need to do in order to marshal your code into something that can be tested.

And that is where the strategy aspect of all of this comes together. Because everything I'm teaching you, you're not going to be doing this blindly. You're going to encounter situations where sometimes you need to not follow the rules, not follow the principles, but you still want to be aware of them.

And that's the thing.

So [00:08:00] when it comes to the physical guess points, and this will make a lot more sense in value first and in the guess points portion of the course. Each of these layers here, each of these specific systems here actually are the various abstraction layers.

The incoming adapter layer, that has to do with infrastructure coming in. The system, that's also infrastructure. The application layer, you can see some of the questions we're asking Do the internals of the system do the right things when we perform scenarios and edge cases?

And are the internals being called properly?

So that is a lot for horizontal decoupling. And we will be attacking this from a number of different angles.

In code first, all I'm going to get you to do is to build out something very basically with MVC.

This is going to be the most straightforward way you can use this to begin to horizontally make sense of where things belong and where things go. And then we're going to take that a little bit further and best practice first, I'm going to make you refactor that to a layered architecture, and you will also learn how to write end to end [00:09:00] tests using a four tier non flaky end to end Test infrastructure.

That is a mouthful of words.

Pattern- first, we're going to learn about the back end patterns, the front end patterns, and in order to enable the testing strategies that you're going to learn here as well, we're going to need to learn about core code and infrastructure code, how to separate them out and how to utilize the ports and adapters architecture.

In responsibility first, we will be looking at the stereotypical architecture. We've talked about this in passing before, but it is one of my favorite concepts in this entire realm of software design, architecture, and testing. When I learned the stereotypical architecture, everything seemed to click because once you learn this, you can make sense of the various libraries and frameworks that are out there in the wild, and you know exactly where to slot them into your architecture in particular.
